cs.SI, cs.CL, cs.SD, cs.CY, cs.SOC

This paper focuses on analyzing social media data, specifically Twitter, to identify demographic information and investigate how different demographic groups connect with each other and differentiate them regarding linguistic styles and interests. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). 

The paper also uses advanced image processing algorithms from Face++ to identify gender and race, which falls under the sub-category cs.CL (Computation and Language). 

Additionally, the paper extracts linguistic features from six categories, which falls under the sub-category cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing). 

The paper also analyzes the topics of interest of Twitter users, which falls under the sub-category cs.CY (Computers and Society). 

Finally, the paper develops a web-based system to provide transparency to the Twitter trending topics system, which falls under the sub-category cs.SOC (Social and Economic Networks).
